<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/13474300-nicole"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1456230074i/13474300._UX100_CR0,38,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/13474300-nicole">Nicole</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">What a terrible way to approach a book. Let&apos;s see -- maybe it&apos;s really well written? Or has compelling characters or a gripping plot or any of the oth<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">What a terrible way to approach a book. Let's see -- maybe it's really well written? Or has compelling characters or a gripping plot or any of the other elements that make books good? <br /><br />Just because the subject matter and/or genre "seem" like they've been done before doesn't mean they can't be done well again. That's the challenge that all writers face, after all -- to take a love story or a man v. nature tale and tell it in a fresh and compelling way. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
